# PR Standards

## Branch Naming

Format: `type/short-kebab-description`

| Prefix | When to use |
|--------|-------------|
| `feat/` | New feature or user-visible capability |
| `fix/` | Bug fix |
| `chore/` | Config, tooling, dependencies, refactoring |
| `hotfix/` | Urgent production fix ‚Äî PR to `main`, then cherry-pick to `dev` |

Examples:
- `feat/property-filter-by-date`
- `fix/kanban-partner-visibility`
- `chore/eslint-config`

**Never branch directly from `main`.** Branch from `dev`. Only release PRs go `dev ‚Üí main`.

## PR Descriptions ‚Äî Language

All PR titles and descriptions MUST be written in English. This is required for:
- GitHub history readability across the team
- AI agent tooling that reads git history
- Consistent audit trail

Commit messages also in English. Code comments may be in Spanish if they explain domain business logic.

## PR Title Format

```
type(scope): brief description
```

Examples:
- `feat(supply): add date range filter to kanban view`
- `fix(reno): correct completion percentage in sidebar`
- `chore(ci): add lint step to PR workflow`

## "How to Test" Section ‚Äî Required

Every PR MUST include a "How to test" section (or "How to verify") with concrete manual steps. No PR should be merged without it.

Good example:
```
- [ ] Go to /supply/kanban as a supply_partner user
- [ ] Open any property card
- [ ] Expect the "Owners" tab to show the list of owners
- [ ] Add a new owner ‚Äî verify it appears immediately without reload
```

Bad example:
```
- [ ] Test the feature
```

## Scope ‚Äî Max ~15 Files

A single PR should touch at most ~10‚Äì15 files. If a change requires more:
- Split into a preparatory PR (refactor/types/plumbing) and a follow-up PR (feature)
- Ask yourself: can the reviewer meaningfully review this in one sitting?

Exceptions: auto-generated files (Supabase types, lock files, migration sequences) don't count toward this limit.

## Protected Zones ‚Äî Do Not Touch

PRs must explicitly note if they touch protected zones:
- `supabase/migrations/**` ‚Äî only add new files, never modify existing
- `lib/auth/**` ‚Äî auth providers
- `app/prophero.css` ‚Äî design tokens

If a PR touches any of these, the description must explain why it was necessary and confirm it was reviewed by a dev.

## Merge Strategy (CRITICAL ‚Äî enforced by GitHub repo settings)

| PR type | Merge strategy | Why |
|---------|---------------|-----|
| Feature ‚Üí `dev` | **Squash & merge** | Keeps `dev` history clean ‚Äî one commit per feature |
| Release `dev ‚Üí main` | **Merge commit (ONLY)** | Preserves shared SHAs so `dev` and `main` stay in sync ‚Äî no phantom divergence |
| Hotfix ‚Üí `main` | **Squash & merge** | Minimal footprint on production branch |
| Hotfix ‚Üí `dev` | Cherry-pick or separate PR | Ensures `dev` gets the fix too |

### Why merge commit is mandatory for releases

Squash merge creates a **brand-new SHA** on `main` that never exists in `dev`. After a squash merge:
- GitHub sees `main` and `dev` as permanently diverged.
- Every subsequent release PR inflates with N phantom commits and duplicate "Files changed".
- The "X commits behind" counter never reaches 0.

A merge commit preserves the original commit SHAs from `dev`, so after the merge both branches share the same history up to that point. The "X commits behind" counter stays at 0.

### GitHub repo setting (must be configured once ‚Äî see GITFLOW-SETUP below)

The repo MUST have these merge button settings:
- **Allow merge commits:** ON (used for `dev ‚Üí main` releases)
- **Allow squash merging:** ON (used for feature ‚Üí `dev` and hotfix ‚Üí `main`)
- **Allow rebase merging:** OFF (prevents accidental rebase merges)

## GitFlow Diagram

```
feature/* ‚îÄ‚îÄsquash‚îÄ‚îÄ‚ñ∂ dev ‚îÄ‚îÄmerge commit‚îÄ‚îÄ‚ñ∂ main ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚ñ∂ GitHub Release (v1.2.0)
                                              ‚îÇ
                                    hotfix/* ‚óÄ‚îÄ‚îò (branch from main)
                                        ‚îÇ
                                        ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄsquash‚îÄ‚îÄ‚ñ∂ main ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚ñ∂ GitHub Release (v1.2.1)
                                        ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄcherry-pick‚îÄ‚îÄ‚ñ∂ dev
```

**Key rules:**
1. Features always target `dev` (squash merge).
2. Releases always go `dev ‚Üí main` (merge commit ‚Äî NEVER squash).
3. Merging to `main` auto-creates a Git tag + GitHub Release (semver: `v1.0.0`, `v1.1.0`, ...).
4. Hotfixes branch from `main`, squash-merge back to `main`, then cherry-pick to `dev`.
5. Never merge `main` back into `dev` ‚Äî the flow is one-way.

## Versioning ‚Äî Semver Tags

Tags follow standard [Semantic Versioning](https://semver.org/):

| Change type | Version bump | Example |
|-------------|-------------|---------|
| Release PR title starts with `feat` | Minor (`v1.1.0 ‚Üí v1.2.0`) | New feature shipped |
| Anything else (fix, chore, hotfix) | Patch (`v1.2.0 ‚Üí v1.2.1`) | Bug fix or maintenance |
| Breaking change | Manual major bump | Requires editing the tag before merge |

Tags and GitHub Releases are created automatically by `.github/workflows/create-release.yml` ‚Äî no manual tagging needed.

## Base Branch

- Feature PRs: base is always `dev`
- Release PRs: `dev ‚Üí main` (created automatically by CI, merged manually by tech lead)
- Hotfix PRs: base is `main`, then cherry-pick to `dev`
- Never open a PR directly to `main` unless it's a release PR or a hotfix

## Branch Sync ‚Äî Unidirectional Flow

The flow is strictly **one-way**: `feature ‚Üí dev ‚Üí main`.

**Never sync `main` back into `dev`.** After a proper merge commit, `dev` and `main` share the same SHAs. Merging `main` back into `dev` is unnecessary and introduces duplicate history.

The only case where `main` has changes that `dev` doesn't is **hotfixes**. Handle those by cherry-picking the hotfix commit into `dev` (or opening a separate PR to `dev`).

## Branch Sync ‚Äî Rebase Before You Start (MANDATORY)

Before creating any feature branch, always sync local `dev` with `origin/dev`:

```bash
git fetch origin
git checkout dev
git rebase origin/dev
```

Before pushing any branch, rebase onto the latest `origin/dev` to minimize conflicts on the PR:

```bash
git fetch origin
git rebase origin/dev
```

**If `git rebase` reports conflicts at either point:**
- Stop immediately. Do not auto-resolve, do not `git rebase --abort` without telling the user.
- List the conflicting files (`git status`).
- Wait for the user to resolve manually and run `git rebase --continue`.
- Never proceed past a failed rebase.

## Branch Naming ‚Äî Enforced Format

All branch names MUST start with one of these prefixes:

| Prefix | When to use |
|--------|-------------|
| `feat/` | New feature or user-visible capability |
| `fix/` | Bug fix |
| `chore/` | Config, tooling, dependencies, refactoring |
| `hotfix/` | Urgent production fix ‚Äî PR targets `main` |

**Agents must reject any branch name that does not match this format.** Do not create the branch. Ask the user for a corrected name before continuing.
